data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — expression tree no longer needed

The setters parameter changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`, so your manual expression tree won't compile. Replace it entirely:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `SetPropertyCalls<T>` expression tree API is gone — you now write imperative code inside a regular lambda.

---

### 2. Complex types — two column-naming changes

**a) Duplicate column names are now uniquified.** Your `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one `Street` column (data corruption risk). EF 10 appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`). To keep explicit control:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use full path in column names.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to column `BillingAddress_City` — it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve old names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

⚠️ Both changes will generate new migrations that rename columns. Pin column names with `HasColumnName` if you don't want schema changes.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

This supports the new constant-redaction feature — `logCommandText` has inlined constants scrubbed unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on.
